##
## References-
##       https://docs.python.org/3/extending/extending.html
##       https://docs.python.org/3.9/extending/building.html
##       https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/tutorials/installing-packages/
##
## Usage notes-
##       Each subdirectory contains a python assembler extension.
##       The subdirectory name is (by convention) the package name.
##
## Package requirements, source-
##       .SDL -> ../../../..
##       .setup.py
##           Contains distutils setup information.
##       LICENSE -> .SDL/.licenses/LICENSE.xxx
##       Makefile.STD
##           Target compile:   python -m build .
##           Target install:   python -m pip install .
##           Target uninstall: python -m pip uninstall package
##       pyproject.toml
##           Contains PIP517 build hooks
##       README.md
##           Markdown format package descriptions
##       packagemodule.c
##           The package source file.
##       tests
##           Package test directory, can be empty.
##
## Package requirements, object-
##       S->(source directory)
##       LICENSE -> S/LICENSE
##       Makefile -> S/Makefile.STD
##       pyproject.toml -> S/pyproject.toml
##       setup.py -> S/.setup.py
##       README.md -> S/README.md
##       packagemodule.c -> S/packagemodule.c
##       tests -> S/tests
##
## Usage notes-
##       All building is done from the object subdirectory.
##
## Build (assemble) a package-
##       make compile               ## Compiles into build subdirectory
##
## Install the package-
##       make install               ## Installs into system site-package
##
## Uninstall the package-
##       make uninstall             ## Uninstalls from system site-package
##       make clean                 ## Removes local directory build files
##       make pristine              ## Same as: make uninstall; make clean
##
